05766nam a22007335i 9781487579968DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191966onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875799687 a10.3138/97814875799682doi  a(DE-B1597)527820  a(OCoLC)1129205191  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0060002bisacsh00aPioneers of Canadian Science / Les Pionniers de la science canadienne /ced. by George Stanley. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1966  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tPREFACE -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tLA TRAME SCIENTIFIQUE DE L'HISTOIRE DU CANADA -- tBIOLOGISTS AND BIOLOGICAL RESEARCH SINCE 1864 -- tL'ABBE LEON PROVANCHER, 1820-1892 -- tL'OUBLIE DE L'HISTOIRE DE LA SCIENCE CANADIENNE -GEORGE LAWSON, 1827-1895 -- tTHE REVEREND JAMES BOVELL, M.D., 1817-1880 -- tSIR JOHN WILLIAM DAWSON, 1820-1899 -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tAPPENDICES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe annual meeting of the Royal Society of Canada for 1964 was held in Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island, where one hundred years previously the first steps towards the confederation of Canada had been taken. It was fitting that this meeting should be related to various developments -- political, economic, and scientific -- in Canada during the preceding one hundred years. The scientific section of the Society presented papers dealing with the history and development of the biological sciences in Canada. As presented in this volume the papers, which represent the fruits of much original research, make an important contribution to our knowledge of the development of scientific thought in Canada, and, by their historical treatment of scientific subjects, provide a means of bridging the gap between scientists and non-scientists. Léon Lortie, in "La Trame scientifique de l'histoire de Canada" (a paper specially prepared for inclusion here) looks back on the circumstances and conditions that encouraged a restricted biological research in Canada, and W. Kanye Lamb and Thomas W.M. Cameron examine biologists and biological research since 1864. Then, distinguished scientists present biographical accounts of four Canadian biologists who have influenced scientific research in this country: G.P. Holland appraises l'Abbé Léon Provancher, a systematic entomologist, in the context of his own time and the present; Jacques Rousseau and William G. Dore discuss George Lawson, whom they call "l'oublié de l'histoire de la science canadienne," despite his important contributions to botanical studies in Canada; C.E. Dolman presents a study of the Reverend James Bovell, M.D., a theologian, philosopher, and physician who had a strong influence on the life and career of Sir William Osler; and T.H. Clark discusses Sir John William Dawson, an outstanding palaeontologist who was especially influential in furthering the progress of geological studies in Canada during the nineteenth century. The chairman of the session was the late Dr. E.G.D. Murray, whose Introduction is included here; a Preface is provided by the Editor of the volume, G.F.G. Stanley, who is Professor of History and Dean of Arts at Royal Military College, Kingston.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aCameron, Thomas W. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, T. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolman, C. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDore, William G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, G.P., econtributor.4ctb4https://i